WEBVTT

00:00:00.979 --> 00:00:02.980
Tonya, welcome to Talk Python To Me.

00:00:03.080 --> 00:00:03.900
It's awesome to have you here.

00:00:04.830 --> 00:00:06.520
Oh my gosh, I'm so excited to be here.

00:00:06.610 --> 00:00:07.760
Thank you for having me, Michael.

00:00:08.259 --> 00:00:09.520
Yeah, you're very welcome.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:11.600
And I'm super excited.

00:00:12.799 --> 00:00:14.220
In a good and bad way,

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:16.059
excited to have you here because I'm

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:17.020
very excited to talk to you.

00:00:17.090 --> 00:00:18.820
But some of the stuff that we're going to talk about

00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:21.640
might be a little unnerving for people out there listening.

00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:25.740
They may pause the show and then run off to make

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:27.600
some changes to what they're doing and then come back.

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:32.119
And that part might be a little exciting in a different way, but it's going to be fun.

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:33.640
Yes, it will.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:40.960
Have you ever had that experience where you're giving a presentation or something and somebody goes gasp in the audience and maybe runs away or something?

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:47.440
I was doing a capture the flag contest once and I was showing people how to do an SQL injection.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.160
And then we just like logged in without a password.

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:53.140
And this woman was like, oh, my gosh.

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:55.640
And she literally just she stood up.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:56.540
She's like, I have to go.

00:00:56.980 --> 00:01:00.900
And she told me the next day she fixed three of them at work.

00:01:01.290 --> 00:01:02.400
And she just stayed all night.

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:04.180
Oh, amazing.

00:01:04.309 --> 00:01:05.300
You made a huge impression.

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:07.980
It was pretty cool.

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:09.680
Yeah, that's pretty awesome.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:15.020
I've never had that around security, but I was doing an in-person class once for database things,

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:16.880
which we're going to touch on databases for sure.

00:01:17.460 --> 00:01:18.840
And this had to do with transactions.

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:25.400
And I said, if you do things this way, it doesn't actually use a transaction unless, oh, yes, it does.

00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:27.040
And I showed that it didn't.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:29.260
And somebody said, I'll be back later.

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:30.120
And they just took off.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:32.820
Oh my gosh, this is not good.

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:34.580
We have to fix this now.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:37.640
So yeah, hopefully no one actually has to do that here.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:40.380
But I'm sure there's a ton for people to learn.

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:45.680
So speaking of learning, let's start with a little bit about you.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.400
You have a domain, shehackspurple.ca, that tells us

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:52.120
several things about you, I believe.

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:53.840
Purple is interesting.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:02:02.260
hacks is interesting and Canada tell us about yourself um so I was a software developer for a

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:08.700
really long time and then I switched to security and when I was a software developer I used to also

00:02:08.899 --> 00:02:15.100
play music in bars and music festivals as sort of my hobby but it was I released albums and did

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:20.079
all of that so that's why I'm quite the public speaker because I've been on stage my whole life

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:26.200
And so I switched to security and I became a pen tester, which is red team.

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:30.160
And like, that's where you attack things and it's offensive security.

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:35.620
And I don't mean we swear at people, but it's the other way around.

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:38.020
I believe that is the direction the swearing probably goes.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:38.380
Right.

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:44.760
But then as I was doing pen testing, I kept sitting with the devs and I would like pair

00:02:44.970 --> 00:02:46.820
program with them and I'd help them fix things.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:50.340
And I'm like, well, if we threat model this, well, and I kept doing app sec, essentially.

00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:54.240
And people are like, you keep doing blue team, you keep doing defenses.

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:56.200
It's like, you can't make up your mind.

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.940
And eventually one of them's like, you're a purple team.

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:05.940
And so I was at a conference in Europe and on stage during the conference, this woman,

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:10.220
she kept playing with her phone on a panel, ignoring the audience.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:11.420
And I was super shocked.

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:16.680
And finally, she's like, I'm really sorry, but she, her company had created WannaCry.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:23.940
by accident yeah and it had just broken out and she's like so there's this virus and it just hit

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:31.580
the nhs and took down the hospitals and this and that and oh my gosh and so everyone like ran out

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:36.200
of the room freaking out and they all went to check twitter because that's where everyone was talking

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:40.860
and so people are like you have to make a twitter account and so i was like oh what will i call

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:46.119
myself and i was like she acts computers and then it was too long because that was my email address

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:52.920
she hacks computers at gmail.com that used to be my email and um but then basically that was too

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:57.120
long so i was like i don't know and someone's like well you know you have that like purple team thing

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:02.480
going so i was like well it's not like anyone will ever follow me so i changed it to she hacks purple

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:08.579
and then turns out that i really so then i put some purple in my hair to tease my friend kevin

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:10.800
and it went all from there.

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.740
Like, yeah.

00:04:14.420 --> 00:04:15.020
That's amazing.

00:04:16.019 --> 00:04:16.160
Yeah.

00:04:16.700 --> 00:04:18.280
It's now part of the vibe, right?

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:18.880
That's awesome.

00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:19.780
That's a really cool story.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:23.240
You said you've been a programmer for a while

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:27.240
and then got into app security and pen testing.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:28.440
How did you get into all that?

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:30.980
It was totally an accident.

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:33.640
So like I said, I was in a band

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:35.660
and so we had this pen tester in our office

00:04:36.120 --> 00:04:37.260
and he was in a band.

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:39.460
And so obviously we became friends.

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:44.680
And one day I came to his desk and I was like, hey, my band wrote this song called Mandatory Dance Party.

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:50.880
And we want to make this mobile app where if you're near someone else that has the app, it goes beep, beep, beep, mandatory dance party.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:52.940
And then you both have to dance or else.

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:55.600
And then whoever jiggles their phone the most wins.

00:04:55.960 --> 00:04:57.400
I'm like, did you want to make this app with me?

00:04:57.580 --> 00:04:58.280
He's like, there's nothing.

00:04:58.610 --> 00:04:59.480
I want to do more.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:02.220
And so our friendship began.

00:05:02.430 --> 00:05:06.180
And then for a year and a half, he just nagged me to become a pen tester.

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:07.380
He's like, you'd be so good.

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:08.660
You'd be really good at it.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.980
You've been doing, you've been a dev for like 17 years.

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:13.320
It's time for something new.

00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:16.200
And I was like, no, I am the king of software.

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:17.560
This is the best.

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.280
I make something out of nothing all day.

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.060
It'll never be cooler than this.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:24.160
But then it turned out it was pretty cool.

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:26.740
And you still get to write code sometimes.

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:30.680
And then eventually I figured out I was not meant to be a pen tester.

00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:31.940
I was meant to do app sec.

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:33.900
So I still get to hang out with devs all day.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:37.080
I'm not alone freezing cold in a data center at night.

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:41.720
and I get to, it's like more like a social butterfly type of job

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:44.480
where a pen tester is more like the lone wolf type of job.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:45.180
Yeah, yeah.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:48.100
You're working on the disassembly, looking for, you know,

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:50.280
fuzzing something, looking for it to crash.

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:55.340
Yeah, so you still get to break stuff in AppSec sometimes,

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:56.980
but like that's not all you do.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.100
You do a lot of conversations, a lot of brainstorming,

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:03.300
and that's better for my extroverted personality.

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:05.520
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:06.980
You have a newsletter.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:08.880
People can visit your website and sign up,

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:10.680
and I'll put links to all those sorts of things

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:12.940
in the show notes for you.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:18.120
So yeah, a couple of things I wanted to talk about.

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:21.040
First of all, I've seen you giving presentations

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:22.680
about threat modeling.

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:24.780
Tell us, what is threat modeling,

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:26.700
and what are some of the takeaways?

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.400
Obviously, our audience here is largely Python developers,

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:36.060
data scientists and a ginormous assorted other

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:38.500
that sort of orbits around those spaces.

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:41.760
But so they'd probably be pretty interested

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:44.740
on the developer data scientist side of threat modeling.

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:47.940
What is it and what's it like for devs?

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:54.440
- So threat modeling is sort of like evil brainstorming.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:57.640
So you get a security person like me in the room,

00:06:58.180 --> 00:07:01.760
you get a dev or one of the technical leads for your system

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:02.880
And then you get the product owner.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:08.080
So the person that understands the business of this app and like why it exists in the world.

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:10.500
And at least those three people.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.320
If more people come, it's better, but that's fine.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:18.100
And then you talk about what could go wrong and what are you going to do about it?

00:07:18.930 --> 00:07:21.940
I have this friend named Adam Shostak who's written a bunch of books about it.

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:27.280
So I used to ask a ton of questions and then I met him and now I ask four things.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:28.920
What are we doing?

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:31.760
And so then I usually draw it out on a whiteboard.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.980
So like, oh, there's an API and it talks to this.

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:34.740
And then this happens.

00:07:34.950 --> 00:07:36.360
And then people steal bikes.

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:36.720
OK.

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:38.660
And then--

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:39.500
JOHN MUELLER: Do we have a database?

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:40.320
Is it in the cloud?

00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:42.540
Is it in a data center that we own?

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:43.300
Whatever, yeah?

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:43.700
Yeah.

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:46.200
And then I ask questions along the way.

00:07:46.370 --> 00:07:48.580
And then I'm like, so what could go wrong here?

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:51.020
And then it's like, these two things are talking.

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:52.380
Do we authenticate first?

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:54.400
Or do we just talk to any old API?

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:57.540
And we go through and we come up with some things

00:07:57.700 --> 00:07:58.500
that could go wrong.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:07:59.940
And we make a list.

00:08:00.470 --> 00:08:03.220
And then I'm like, okay, so what are we going to do about these things?

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:07.680
And you talk about basically, is this a serious risk?

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:08.720
Is it scary?

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:11.740
Or is it like, you know what, if that happens, it's not really a big deal.

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:14.180
And the likelihood is really, really rare.

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:15.860
So maybe we'll accept that risk.

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:21.500
But a lot of them, it's like, you know, if we added a certificate here, or we included

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:24.400
authentication there, like we can make some small changes.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.880
And if you're during the design phase of the system development life cycle, it costs you nothing, right?

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:33.880
Usually it costs you nothing or very little.

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:39.780
And so then you basically improve your design and then you write it all out.

00:08:39.810 --> 00:08:43.539
And then hopefully someone approves these changes.

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:48.420
And then at the end, a thing that Adam asks is, did we do a good job?

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:50.900
And that is the magical question.

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:57.040
because the very first time I did one of these in the government, I did not realize that that's what

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:02.560
I was doing to my director. I was like, well, what about this? And what about that? And this could go

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:06.600
wrong. And because I was trying to kill the project because I thought it was a terrible

00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:12.160
pro and we did end up canceling it. But I brought up like all these huge existential risks to this

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:17.159
ridiculous project they're thinking of doing. And he just kept saying, it'll be fine. And I'll manage

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:22.500
that risk and i i was like you realize manage that risk means nothing right you're gonna do nothing

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:26.880
so i brought up eight really big risks and you want to do nothing about any of them i'm like are

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:30.940
we doing it like do you think we've done a good job here like you feel proud today because i don't

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:37.420
and then we started again and then eventually over the months we cancelled the project because

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:43.180
it was quite silly um just to be clear i usually love it when software development projects go

00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:48.120
forward. This was a very special situation where it was not in the taxpayers' best interest.

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:53.360
Yes. Anyway, I'm like, there's more there, but I'm like, NDAs.

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:54.440
Yeah, of course.

00:09:55.430 --> 00:10:02.080
But usually we come up with a couple of changes that grossly reduce the risk of the system.

00:10:03.879 --> 00:10:10.160
And it's quite fun. Once you start... So the first time I went to a threat model,

00:10:10.420 --> 00:10:17.420
I came with my dev background of I will fix any problem you bring to me. I just need to do code

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:21.680
and I can fix whatever you need. But it's different when it's like, I'm going to try to break things.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:26.880
You have to learn kind of this new skill set of like, how can I make it do stuff it should not do?

00:10:27.959 --> 00:10:33.460
And it took me a while and now I'm brutal. Like I go to the movies, I'm like, we could have gotten free.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:37.880
It's even outside of technology now, huh?

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:39.320
Oh, yeah.

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:40.720
Oh, it's everywhere now.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:41.100
Yeah.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:44.520
My significant other who does not work in tech will be like,

00:10:44.820 --> 00:10:46.720
I'm just trying to threat model this for the kids.

00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:50.820
If we go to the pool, they'll have wet bathing suits.

00:10:53.920 --> 00:10:54.460
Yeah, yeah.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:55.060
Very nice.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:11:01.700
You know, I think there's two different ways to look at this, right?

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:08.360
obviously from a developer perspective, you've got to look at, well, what packages or libraries

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:14.780
am I using? And how are we validating input and all those kinds of things? And I feel like that's

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:20.940
one level, but maybe the threat modeling is a little bit broader. Like, are we storing stuff

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:28.120
unencrypted anywhere? Who could get that? And it's the thing that makes me nervous. I said I would

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:31.800
be somewhat nervous about this at the beginning. The stuff that makes me nervous about all of these

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:33.840
is the asymmetry of it.

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:36.840
As a developer or data scientist

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:39.640
or somebody in charge of this information and the systems,

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:43.660
you have to be right all the time, right?

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:45.380
And if you're ever not right,

00:11:45.660 --> 00:11:47.400
little Bobby tables is on you like nothing.

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:49.400
It's bad.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:51.720
It's like a goalie, right?

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:53.980
Like you let it go goals and everyone's like,

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:54.460
you're the worst.

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:57.220
And it's like, I defended against hundreds of shots.

00:11:58.020 --> 00:11:58.780
Do I get nothing?

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:00.260
Exactly.

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:03.920
Well, developers shouldn't be on their own in this.

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:05.320
So that's the whole thing.

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:13.680
So like the job of the AppSec person, in my opinion, is to support the developers in making more secure apps, right?

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:25.020
So booking a threat modeling time with them or, you know, providing a stack analysis tool or a secret scanner or whatever to scan their code so that they can make better code.

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:37.360
So they have help giving them training, giving them like a list of super clear requirements at the beginning of the project rather than at the end telling them it's wrong.

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:39.620
That is a huge one.

00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:46.580
Like if someone's going to build an API, I would prefer the API be behind an API gateway if it's publicly accessible.

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:54.060
And I want to do things like turn on authentication and authorization and rate limiting and all sorts of fancy, nice, awesome stuff that they offer.

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:59.320
And so I tell them at the very beginning of the project, I don't wait until the end.

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:01.140
And I'm like, well, this design is all wrong.

00:13:02.460 --> 00:13:03.460
Where's your rate limiting?

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:04.240
Yeah.

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:06.500
But that's what we did back in the day.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:13.700
Like when I had my first vulnerability assessment done, I'm supposed to go to prod in two days.

00:13:13.870 --> 00:13:18.540
And they ran the world's crappiest dynamic scanner on my app.

00:13:18.990 --> 00:13:21.040
And they're like, you have cross-site scripting.

00:13:21.130 --> 00:13:22.240
And this was so long ago.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:26.740
I searched for cross-site scripting on the internet and there was only three web pages.

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:28.800
So I'm old, everyone.

00:13:31.740 --> 00:13:33.920
And one was this thing called OWASP.

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:36.020
And I was like, what the heck is that?

00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:40.680
And it took me quite a while to figure out how to fix it, right?

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:47.040
Like we've come a long way, but yeah, the developer shouldn't be alone in this anymore.

00:13:47.390 --> 00:13:48.500
They should have help.

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:51.360
I'm not saying that every company does have that.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:52.540
I'm saying every company should.

00:13:52.680 --> 00:13:57.720
If you have a bunch of devs, you should have eventually a security person that supports them.

00:13:59.060 --> 00:13:59.140
Right.

00:13:59.420 --> 00:14:09.820
Maybe sits with them for a few hours a week or a month or something and sort of, as you said, like a butterfly sort of moves around the team, hanging out with other people.

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:11.060
Like, oh, you work on the API.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:11.360
Okay.

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:14.340
Let me hang out with you a bit this morning.

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:17.120
Ideally, that would be great.

